We generate k symptom-based search query sets using the k = 19 identified symptoms from the FF100 survey for COVID-19 (Supplementary Table 1)23. We also consider one additional set that includes specific COVID-19 terminology, i.e. the “COVID-19” keyword itself among others. Query sets may include different wordings for the same symptom or queries with minor grammatical differences (especially for queries in Greek and French). If a symptom is represented by more than one search query, then we obtain the total frequency (sum) across these queries. Each query set time series is smoothed using a harmonic mean over the past 14 days (see Supplementary Eq. 4 for a definition of the harmonic mean), and any trends across the entire period of the analysis are removed using linear detrending. We then apply a min-max normalisation (Supplementary Eq. 1) to the frequency time series of each query set to obtain a balanced representation between more and less frequent searches. We divide our data into two periods of interest, the current one (from September 30, 2019 until May 24, 2020) and a historical one (from September 30, 2011 to September 29, 2019). The corresponding data sets are denoted by \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
